ğŸ”¹ What are Variables in Terraform?
Variables let you parameterize Terraform configurations.

Instead of hardcoding values (like AMI ID, instance type, region), you define them as variables.

This makes Terraform code reusable, flexible, and easier to manage across environments (dev, qa, prod).

ğŸ‘‰ Think of variables like function arguments in programming.

ğŸ”¹ Types of Variables in Terraform
Input variables â†’ values you pass into Terraform.

Output variables â†’ values Terraform gives back after running.

Local variables â†’ temporary values defined inside code.

ğŸ”¹ How to Store Variables in Terraform?
1. Define variables in variables.tf
# variables.tf
variable "region" {
  description = "AWS region"
  default     = "us-east-1"
}

variable "instance_type" {
  description = "EC2 instance type"
  default     = "t2.micro"
}
2. Use variables in main code
# main.tf
provider "aws" {
  region = var.region
}

resource "aws_instance" "my_ec2" {
  ami           = "ami-123456"
  instance_type = var.instance_type
}
3. Assign variable values
There are multiple ways:

âœ… (a) Default values (in variables.tf)
If you give default, Terraform will use it automatically.

âœ… (b) Use terraform.tfvars file
# terraform.tfvars
region        = "us-west-2"
instance_type = "t3.small"
Terraform automatically loads terraform.tfvars.

âœ… (c) Use environment variables
export TF_VAR_region=us-east-2
export TF_VAR_instance_type=t3.medium
Terraform will automatically pick them up.

âœ… (d) Use -var flag in CLI
terraform apply -var="region=ap-south-1" -var="instance_type=t2.large"
4. Output variables
Outputs are used to display values after apply.

output "instance_ip" {
  value = aws_instance.my_ec2.public_ip
}
ğŸ‘‰ After terraform apply, it prints the public IP of EC2.

ğŸ”¹ Real-Time AWS Example
Suppose you want to deploy different EC2 instance types for dev and prod.

Step 1 â€“ variables.tf
variable "env" {
  description = "Environment name"
}

variable "instance_type" {
  description = "EC2 instance type"
}
Step 2 â€“ terraform.tfvars
env           = "dev"
instance_type = "t2.micro"
Step 3 â€“ main.tf
provider "aws" {
  region = "us-east-1"
}

resource "aws_instance" "my_ec2" {
  ami           = "ami-123456"
  instance_type = var.instance_type
  tags = {
    Name = "EC2-${var.env}"
  }
}
Step 4 â€“ Apply
terraform apply
âœ… In dev, it creates an EC2 tagged EC2-dev.
If you change terraform.tfvars to:

env           = "prod"
instance_type = "t3.medium"
and re-run â†’ Terraform creates EC2-prod.

ğŸ”¹ Best Practices for DevOps Engineers
Keep all variables in variables.tf for clarity.

Use terraform.tfvars (or *.auto.tfvars) for environment-specific values.

Never hardcode secrets (use AWS Secrets Manager, SSM Parameter Store, or environment variables).

Use outputs to expose important info (IP, DNS, bucket name) for other tools (like Jenkins/Ansible).

âœ… In interviews, say:

"In Terraform, variables make configurations reusable and environment-friendly. I usually define them in variables.tf, assign values in terraform.tfvars or through environment variables, and use them inside .tf files with var.<name>. For example, in AWS, I can deploy EC2 instances of different types in dev, qa, and prod without changing the main codeâ€”just by changing variable values."

